    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks but i dont think its the water, i've been pretty consistent with that. could it be a lack of nitrogen or something? i read online that yellowing lower leaves usually means a nutrient issue. how do i check if the pH or nitrogen is the problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, the yellowing of lower leaves can often be a sign of nitrogen deficiency. To check if the pH is right and if nitrogen is the problem, you can use a soil test kit. These kits can help you determine the pH level of your soil and the presence of various nutrients, including nitrogen. Most tomato plants prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH (around 6.0 to 7.0). If the pH is outside this range, it can affect nutrient availability. To address nitrogen deficiency, you can add a balanced, slow-release fertilizer specifically formulated for tomatoes. Follow the instructions on the fertilizer package for proper application. Remember, always handle fertilizers with care, and avoid over-applying, as it can harm your plants. If you're unsure or concerned, a visit to a local garden center or extension office can provide personalized advice.",
