    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i'll get a test kit. but why does it happen just to the bottom leaves though? it feels like something is actually stealing the nutrients from the plant before it can even reach the top. is there any way to tell if the soil is just \"empty\" or if something is actively preventing the plant from taking it up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing of lower leaves, a condition known as chlorosis, often occurs due to the plant's inability to transport nutrients from the soil to the leaves effectively. This can happen for several reasons, including poor soil structure, compacted soil, or a high concentration of salts, which can \"block\" the plant's ability to absorb nutrients, making it seem like the soil is \"empty.\"\n\nTo determine if your soil is compacted or if there's an issue with nutrient availability, you can perform a simple soil test. Look for signs of soil compaction by feeling the soil; if it's very hard and dry, it may be compacted. You can also try gently poking a finger into the soil to see if it breaks easily; if not, it's likely compacted. For a more detailed analysis, consider sending a soil sample to a local extension office or garden center. They can provide a comprehensive nutrient profile and recommendations for amending your soil to ensure your tomato plants have access to the nutrients they need. Improving soil structure through the addition of organic matter, such as compost, can also help alleviate compaction and enhance nutrient availability.",
